JOHANNESBURG - Consumer Price Inflation (CPI) slowed dropped to its lowest level since March 2015 down to 4.4 percent in January 2018, from 4.7 percent in December 2017. StatSA said food and non-alcoholic beverages contributed 0.2 of a percentage to the decline. A drop in transport prices contributed 0.1 of a percentage point and miscellaneous goods and services contributing 0.1 of a percentage point to the drop. The CPI drop is good news for consumers and could encourage the Reserve Bank to drop interest rates. #CPI down to lowest level since March 2015 as inflation eases to 4,4% in January 2018 from 4,7% in December 2017 #StatsSA https://t.co/U3dhp7bSZD pic.twitter.com/hnxO3kHtre #Food non-alcoholic beverages #inflation down to 4,5% in January 2018. #CPI January 2018=4,4% #StatsSA https://t.co/U3dhp7bSZD #Fruit prices down by 1,1% between December 2017 and January 2018. #CPI January 2018=4,4% #StatsSA https://t.co/U3dhp7bSZD Stocking your schoolbag was slightly cheaper in January 2018 compared with December 2017. #CPI January 2018=4,4% #StatsSA https://t.co/U3dhp7bSZD pic.twitter.com/pzZ4ujdY6A eNCA